post_title: What is it like to study at UNSW Australia?
post_content: What is it like to study at UNSW Australia?
reply_content: I have recently finished my degree at UNSW, so I’ll tell you the following: Social Aspect: As others have stated, UNSW will have a LOT of Asian students. By rough estimation along walking the main walkway and surroundings, I’d dare say that at least 50% of UNSW is Chinese (comprising of international students, ABCs and others). If you don’t mind dealing and walking around with Asian people then this should be no problem. I have noticed that there’s quite a strong selective school culture here too. There’s a saying that for Sydney Boys/Sydney Girls High School students, attending UNSW feels exactly the same as attending school - just extend the bus ride down Anzac parade. Coming into UNSW during my first year, I didn’t feel any culture shock at UNSW because the selective school/tutoring culture was very prevalent. You would frequently see students who went tutoring with you in younger years (prep for selective tests and HSC) only to meet them at the same uni. There’s a LOT of societies at UNSW too. They range from your faculty clubs (Business Society, Actuarial Society, Mathematics Society, Engineering Society etc.), to career based clubs (UNIT, UCC, ECS, etc.) to fun based clubs (AnimeUNSW, Kpop Society, D2MG, etc.). Join them to make friends and connections that will potentially last you a life time. Not to mention that ARC membership (mostly a requirement to join clubs) is free if you’re a student of UNSW. In terms of food offerings, on campus there is Guzman Y Gomez (Mexican), Malaysian, Vietnamese, Chinese, Indian and a few other offerings. Coffee carts are great and coffee at UNSW is very good quality (at least compared to abroad). If you want better eats then you can go along Anzac parade to Kingsford and you’ll find plenty of Chinese, Japanese, Malaysian, Thai eateries. Go east and you’ll see Randwick for more food options including Coles and Woolworths for shopping. For drinking and partying you have the Roundhouse and the Whitehouse. The Roundhouse got a refurbishment lately so apparently it looks nice (I haven’t been myself). Don’t forget about Whitehouse Wednesdays (cheaper alcohol after 4pm). Roundhouse parties are pretty good too from what I’ve heard (although I don’t attend them). UNSW is a lot less political overall. This means that Arc board and SRC student elections will not have much of an impact on campus life compared to USYD and other universities where student politics plays a huge impact on campus life. The most political it became was just the issue of the BSOC elections and CEVSOC elections a few years ago, and that activity is tame compared to what happens at USYD. The Campus: Tbh the university campus is quite compacted. Lots of buildings that are at least 7–8 storeys high (building up) which is necessary due to the lack of land available. However that means that getting to and from places should take no more than 10 minutes. On the other hand UNSW does have heaps of stairs if you need to walk up from lower to upper campus. The Basser steps it is. Which means walking up and down might take a toll on your energy levels but will certainly improve your fitness levels. There’s some green area (village green, village lawn, physics lawn, naked lady lawn, globe lawn, library lawn) but most of UNSW is a concrete slab. That said still a lot of Instagram-worthy sites though. You can also tell UNSW is really making bank as evident by construction of new buildings, demolitions to existing buildings so it can build new ones. You can see all the crane towers on campus too. So as you walk by there is not a single time that you cannot hear construction noises. Faculties: As a general rule, undergrad at UNSW is quite difficult of a uni (compared to universities in the US, but easier than Singapore or India). You have to work hard to obtain good grades. Passing isn’t easy for many subjects (they recently got rid of pass conceeded grades) unless if you study smart and effective. Overall, lecturers are quite decent and willing to help. Unlike the US, your tutors here are normally 2nd, 3rd year+, honours, masters or PhD students (and they are not called TAs), however there are chances you can have lecturers as tutors depending on cohort sizes. Most of them are quite willing to help. In this section I’ll only comment on the faculties I know: UNSW Business School: UNSW Engineering: UNSW CSE (Computer Science and Engineering): Administration: As Imad Hashmi stated, UNSW does feel run like a business. Everything feels very efficiently run here. Enrolment, adding details, paying fees, deferring payment using HECS, course administration, receiving results all done online and can be done yourself. However, overloading courses and approving timetable clashes need to be approved in person (the only manual thing). You can do your timetable yourself, which is a great thing since you can dictate when you come to class (if you even go) so you can deal with part time and/or full time work. I know a lot of students do this and that’s how they get a foot in the door after graduation while studying at uni at the same time. Not only that I’ve noticed UNSW administrative staff are more willing to help you and try to get your needs met (compared to other unis). You can see that they’re desperate for money but they will work for it. Not to mention that I’ve used services over the phone and I did not wait anymore than 5 minutes on the online. Speak of efficiency. Special consideration requests are usually very lenient too (compared to USYD, where it is quite uniform and strict). Job prospects out of UNSW: For one there is UNSW Careers and Employment - so use that service if you’e having trouble finding a job/internship. Other than that I know that when I attend a lot of assessment centres (another fancy word for group interview), half of the room is full of UNSW people and other familiar faces. Also note that UNSW has one of the highest employment rates of the G08 universities. Not only to mention that UNSW produces the most millionaires in Australia of all universities combined. I noticed a few of my friends decided to do startups too, so tag along with that.

post_title: Is UNSW the MIT of Australia?
post_content: Is UNSW the MIT of Australia?
reply_content: For parochial reasons, Australian National University (ANU) has funding thrown at it by the politicians because it’s in Canberra. It would be a bit embarrassing if the nation’s capital (which is in reality a small provincial city) had a provincial university to go along with it. It’s portrayed as Australia’s #1 research University. Whether this is actually the case I could not say for sure. Over he past few years Melbourne Uni has consistently been rated the #1 university in Australia. At other times this has not been the case. From what I hear, UNSW is good but I would not call it the MIT of Australia. UNSW is basically the Sydney equivalent of Monash Uni in Melbourne. You’ll find that Australian Universities generally have a strong focus on a small number of ‘boutique’ disciplines that get all the funding and prestige. Depending on the Uni this might be in IT or biotech, or medicine or solar power (or whatever). Don’t be surprised if some of the prestigious Australian Universities actually offer some average quality courses and vice versa.

post_title: How good is UNSW?
post_content: How good is UNSW?
reply_content: Its good, but no where near as good as its marketing depicts it. I’ve worked and studied there, but like many other universities across the world it has become a business. Large class sizes and overwhelmed teaching staff make it quite unpleasant if you’re ever looking for help with your work. In terms of a social life its quite poor too, many students i’ve met leave disappointed with the lack of engagement they’ve had socially at UNSW. Things also suggests it could get notably worse in the not too distant future. It is moving towards trimesters in 2019 to maximise their income from students, and cutting support staff in some key areas which will likely impact the student experience. They will also be moving some academics to solely teaching positions which will mean that quality academics may look to leave UNSW and go somewhere they can continue their research. It will also mean in some cases students are not being taught by academics whose teaching is informed or influenced by current research. I’m not sure why you’re asking, but if it is about potentially going to UNSW i would suggest you properly think about why you want to go there. Don’t get me wrong, it has quite a good reputation but with whats in store for the future things may change.

post_title: How hard Is it to get into UNSW?
post_content: How hard Is it to get into UNSW?
reply_content: Actually it isn’t very hard for international students trying to study to enter UNSW. I’ve known Chinese and Arab students who used the Foundation Programme set up by UNSW to allow students to enter the courses relevant to their streams. There are Foundations in Sciences, which gets students to enter the Science-related degree streams, Foundations in Design which is more towards Architecture and Design at UNSW Art and Design, and Foundations in Art, which allows student to enter the philosophy side of the degree programme. I say that although this is a very easy and surefire way to enter uni, even if you are a local student, there is a catch: You need to maintain your GPA (or WAM) in your course and make sure you don’t fail or you’ll need to retake. IELTS is also mandatory with an 8 (Last time i checked it was 7.5 but you might as well go 8 for better reasons- also relevant if you’re applying for a Visa) and you will need your high school leaving cert to show your potential to study that course. Its really gruelling, but rewards those who dare to finish this intense course in a year’s time. I got in with my ATAR which was a 91, and i went for design. For most Australians who desire to enter UNSW, it can be tough, but through the Foundation programme and ……a hefty amount of money, you will have a surefire way to enter the university!

post_title: Does a PhD from UNSW Canberra count as the same as a PhD from UNSW?

reply_content: The PhD you get from UNSW@Canberra is a PhD from UNSW. It does not matter which campus you study at; the degree is the same. Your experience as a student at the Canberra/ADFA campus will be quite different from the student experience you’d have in Sydney, however. Weigh that up, as you are likely to be there for a while.

post_title: Is there a rivalry between UNSW and the University of Sydney?
post_content: Is there a rivalry between UNSW and the University of Sydney?
reply_content: Minor edits incorporated Nov 5: Of course! Both are in the Sydney area, about 6-7 km apart, and both are ranked among the best universities in Australia. (The University of Sydney and UNSW are both members of the Group of Eight (Go8) - a coalition of research-intensive Australian universities.)  There are, however, marked differences between the institutions: Sydney University was founded in 1850; UNSW almost exactly 100 year later, in 1949. Sydney University prides itself on its long history, beautiful sandstone campus and the fact that it was modeled after Oxford and Cambridge. UNSW was founded post WWII to meet the growing need to have a university focused on training engineers and technology-related professionals. In contrast to the University of Sydney, UNSW is more a "new world" institution modeled on US research-intensive universities such as MIT. Both are outstanding universities with strong programs in teaching and research across most disciplines. Universities everywhere now compete for dwindling Government dollars, philanthropic support, the very best students and international acclaim. Given that these two outstanding institutions are separated by just a few miles, it is not surprising that they are rivals. It really can't be any other way. Note added: I was concerned that the word "rivalry" carried a negative connotation, but the dictionary definition does not suggest that at all: "competition for the same objective or for superiority in the same field."

post_title: Which is better, UNSW or USyd for engineering foundation program?
post_content: Which is better, UNSW or USyd for engineering foundation program?
reply_content: I completed a Bachelor of Engineering (Electrical) at the University of Sydney and then did a Masters in Biomedical Engineering at UNSW. I agree with Conor O’Driscoll’s answer that Sydney in the late 1980s was quite mathematical and theoretical. I found UNSW in the early 1990s more practical with assignments having more real-life applications. The Sydney degree was quite generalist; we looked at many different topics in Electrical Engineering. The only specialisation was in the Project work in the last year and we had to complete a 6 week industrial placement. Other universities might require greater specialisation at an earlier stage. The Sydney approach let us try out different topics and electives, which can be helpful if you are still learning about yourself and what you like to study. I feel that the Sydney course could lead to work in a Research and Development environment, while the UNSW course would be more practical for general industry. I personally found it tougher to get higher marks at Sydney, though that might have been due to being older at UNSW, and maturity of study methods would have helped. We did have very good students at University of Sydney, who scored very highly in the HSC, but you no doubt would find that is the case also at UNSW. Sydney is a lovely campus, but I liked UNSW too, and felt that their libraries were both very helpful for my work. I feel that the lecturers at UNSW were more approachable and helpful than Sydney, but things could have changed by now. We were also a smaller group in the Centre for Biomedical Engineering which could explain that. I hope this answer assists you.

post_title: Which university should I choose for a PhD in machine learning, UNSW, UTS or USYD?
post_content: Which university should I choose for a PhD in machine learning, UNSW, UTS or USYD?
reply_content: Make your decision based on: 1 how you like the style of each of your potential supervisors 2 which university is most aligned with your long term strategy (ie. Whatever you want to do after your PhD, you might as well get closer to it during your PhD) 3 which university will motivate you the most ? You'll need plenty of motivation for the long journey ahead, so consider which one feels right. This might be driven by friends, location, scholarship, lifestyle etc. What NOT to base your decision on: general public’s perception of the prestige of a particular university. If you're planning on seeking employment in Australia during/afterwards, remember that unlike many places in the world, Australians really don’t care about the reputation of the university you went to. During my career I've recruited or assisted recruiting folk into many desirable corporate roles. Human Resources and decision makers in the hiring proces are abolutely looking for the best individual, and don’t consider perceived prestige of a university as a factor in hiring someone. Maybe there are some niche pockets in Australia where an employer responds to this factor, but I would avoid them at all costs. In theory, I would concede that a University's reputation in a very specific sub-specialty could be a factor to another person with detailed knowledge of that sub-specialty… But in reality, fields of knowledge change so quickly, that such reputations would change between your current choice of university and your eventual PhD completion. Good luck.

You will fit well in teams comprising of people from different nationalities and cultural backgrounds. If you are lucky enough to have few close friends from some Non-English linguistic backgrounds, you might even learn new languages. It is often beneficial to have an international experience when you are still young as being a young person makes you more open to learning and trying new things.

post_title: What is the difference between computer science and software engineering at UNSW?
post_content: What is the difference between computer science and software engineering at UNSW?
reply_content: Felix made some good point but I suppose a SE perspective on the topic would also be helpful! (Assuming Felix is/was doing a CS degree). I’m currently doing Software Engineering at a University in the same state, and someone I know is doing it in UNSW. For this answer I will focus on the UNSW program. CS is more flexible with less compulsory courses, and therefore it will allow you to do more electives in CS as well as other faculties. Software Engineering, on the other hand, is much more structured. AFAIK there is 1 elective available for the first year and 1–2 at second year. For example I wanted to do a logic course next semester, but due to my SE degree requirement, I have to do database instead. The degree is more flexible in year 3 with the “gen-ed”(i.e. courses that are not in the faculty) component. So what are some of the strength of a software engineering degree? The compulsory engineering units focus on many non-technical skill. This include Team work, project management, prototyping, report writing etc. These soft skills, while sounds mundane, are essential for many software development jobs. Of course these can be learnt with the electives from CS. It is easier, however, to learn in a structure designed for these purposes. (Side note: I believe in UNSW SE compulsory is mostly team-project based, and last-semester first year project is building a working, self-navigating robot!) Another (possible) benefit is that because it is structured, employers know you must have written more than a few detailed report, participated in several team-based project, and completed an internship. This might marginally increase your employment prospect. My personal opinion: check out the compulsory courses for each degree, and if you’re sure that you wouldn’t mind doing the SE one then go for it. If you’re not too sure which area of CS you want to focus on or you want to do a minor in another area then do CS. Final word: Since the degrees are so similar, transferring between them will not be a hustle, so don’t be too worry that you’re making the wrong choice! See the following website for a sample degree structure. None None (Note: the SE link is 2014 so there might be slight differences)

post_title: When are all the outcomes for international scholarship applications finalized at UNSW?

post_title: How can I reach UNSW from Sydney International Airport?
post_content: How can I reach UNSW from Sydney International Airport?
reply_content: Public Transport will be safe unless you are travelling late at night alone in dodgy areas. The airport and areas around UNSW should be safe enough. I am guessing your flight will arrive during the day as no flights are permitted to land before 6 am. If you use Google Maps and select the option for Public Transport, you will find the relevant buses and routes that you could take. It also provides you with an estimate of the time of travel. Ordinary public buses don’t have storage racks for your bags but this does not mean you can’t hop onto the bus with your bags. It simply depends on how strong you are and how must time and effort you want to put into lugging your luggage around. Please bear in mind that if the Google Maps option provided is a Train plus a Bus, you will incur an Airport Surcharge (Station Access Fee) of between A$5.60 to A$13.80 plus the normal train fare and then you would incur another far for the Bus to UNSW. Hence overall, I would recommend taking an Uber or Taxi for convenience. Once you are more settled in Sydney you can further save time and cost by buying an Opal Card to help you get around. Other Resources: Getting to and from Sydney Airport Trip planner

post_title: If someone has an offer from Oxford, Australia National University & UNSW, where should one go?
post_content: If someone has an offer from Oxford, Australia National University & UNSW, where should one go?
reply_content: Well, as someone who did his own DPhil at Oxford, I have to admit I’m biased - but Oxford is not an experience to be missed. No, it’s not cheap, though to be fair Sydney’s not a cheap place to live either (I can’t comment on Canberra). There would undoubtedly be ways both to increase your income (e.g. by tutoring) and to reduce your costs (e.g. by sharing with other students) at any of the universities. I managed with little more than my own scholarship when I was there, and even now, over 40 years later, I remain grateful that I chose Oxford. You are going to study in the same city as Edmund Halley did in the 17th Century, Lewis Carroll in the 19th. You’ll eat and drink in places that were frequented by C S Lewis, J R R Tolkien and more prime ministers of England than probably all other British Universities put together. You’ll stroll down the streets where Oscar Wilde was a student, you can see the faded ceiling murals painted by the pre-Raphaelite brotherhood in the Oxford Union. And you’ll get a great education which will be respected the world over. Don’t miss this opportunity… :-)

post_content: Is masters in mechanical/aeronautical difficult in a good university (UNSW for example)?
reply_content: As a Masters student in Electrical Engineering at UNSW Australia, I think I am in a position to answer your question. It really depends on the type of Masters you are looking for. There are two types of PG courses in Au. PG by coursework and PG by research. If you aremore interested in a PG by research it is very competitive. post_title: As a foundation student in the UNSW in Sydney, how to improve my English speaking?
post_content: As a foundation student in the UNSW in Sydney, how to improve my English speaking?
reply_content: Use Merriam-Webster online Dictionary and Thesaurus, which has an audio providing the pronunciation also. Or any other. None Listening well and reading intently are the first steps in good oral and written communication. Build your knowledge of grammar (Wren & Martin), syntax, vocabulary and so on. Before you use a particular word, say “beautiful”, check the online thesaurus for synonyms and use the most appropriate word. Vocabulary is built brick by brick. So learning one new word leads to learning many others. Check the exact meaning of every new word from the dictionary, instead of trying to guess the meaning from its context. Read a lot of good authors. Listen to a lot of good speakers. Yet, in either case, develop your own unique style. Write short speeches, memorize them, internalise them and deliver them before the mirror or a better speaker than you. Practice makes perfect. Join a local Toastmasters Club or other public speaking club. None

post_title: How is the Bachelor’s of Construction Management in Bond University compared to UNSW?
post_content: How is the Bachelor’s of Construction Management in Bond University compared to UNSW?
reply_content: Thanks for the ask2answer. None Qilt is an Australian government site where the graduates of all the courses compare teaching quality, course quality, learning resources and graduate outcomes. Bond or UNSW would be a tough decision, as they are both excellent universities. Bond is a much smaller university, you’ll get more personal attention, small classes (max 12 in a tutorial). Whereas UNSW is a much bigger university, larger courses with many more students in it, probably better known than Bond, but a lot more students, and you may find it harder to access facilities there. None UNSW is probably not as structured although they will have careers support, although their position in the eastern suburbs of Sydney means that their graduate outcomes are good because they are close to Australia’s largest commercial hub. Both universities are in different locations, Bond on the Gold Coast and UNSW in Sydney. Bond is close to surf beaches, and the area is beautiful, whereas UNSW is in the middle of a huge city and unless you have lots of money you may not be able to live in the eastern suburbs close to UNSW (the eastern suburbs are the nicest and most expensive part of Sydney). UNSW has a campus that was built in the 1960s, although they have a number of new buildings to make it nicer. The Bond campus is smaller, but really beautiful. The UNSW is in a really built up area of Sydney, whereas Bond has ovals, and fresh air, and space. At Bond more of the students live on campus or nearby, and it is close knit and quite social communtiy, so probably easier to make friends there. It can be harder to make friends at a large metropolitan university like UNSW where most students don’t live on campus. Bond is considered a “rich” university as a private university, but UNSW is in a really rich area of Sydney too but not as expensive as Bond for Australian students. It’s a tough choice, as they are both really good options. Perhaps decide if you want to live in Sydney or the Gold Coast, and go from there. Good luck!

post_title: Is it possible for me to be an investment banker in NYC if I do a degree from UNSW? My GPA is around 3.9 (adjusted).
post_content: Is it possible for me to be an investment banker in NYC if I do a degree from UNSW? My GPA is around 3.9 (adjusted).
reply_content: UNSW = University of New South Wales…? If so, it’s going to be very hard for you to make that trade as a fresh-from-college hire. Apart from the logistical challenges of building connections with New York-based IB employers, there’s the almost totally prohibitive issue of securing US work authorization, which you probably can’t do right out of the gate. Now, perhaps you have US work authorization by virtue of being born to an American parent. Alternatively, you could try getting married to an American (which worked for me!), although that may not quite line up with your wider life plans. Other than by these avenues, there is pretty much no way for even the most motivated of employers to secure a US work visa for you as an entry-level hire. Other than this, the most likely avenue would involve starting out with a local investment banking employer that has a large presence in the United States. Macquarie comes to mind in this respect. There are also plenty of US banks with growing operations in Sydney, so those could represent pathways too. Once you’ve worked for at least a year in a non-US office of a firm, that organization can obtain an L-1 visa for you that enables you to work for that same organization in the US.

post_title: Which one is better: studying Data Science at UNSW, Computer Science at University of Sydney, or Mathematics at Australian National University?
post_content: Which one is better: studying Data Science at UNSW, Computer Science at University of Sydney, or Mathematics at Australian National University?
reply_content: None Details: “I really like those 3 fields, hence I applied to different majors for all the universities. I am mostly interested at the student environment and also job offers (as an international student).” Until you are admitted to universities, you will not have the actual costs of attendance, and the fact that you have three different majors, you do not have clear cut benefits. What this means is you cannot do a cost benefit analysis to determine which university is the better economic choice. As far as job placement, job placement depends on what you accomplished in your program and cannot be predicted a priori because the number of available jobs depends on a future volatile job market. From an employment prospective, computer science has more entry level jobs than data science or mathematics. Finally, student environment is too subjective to be a deciding factor. Australian National University is located in the capital, so student experience would be different from both UNSW and University of Sydney that have access to Sydney.

post_title: I have to choose between two universities, UNSW Australia and University at Buffalo USA, for bachelors in Computer Science. Which should I pick?
post_content: I have to choose between two universities, UNSW Australia and University at Buffalo USA, for bachelors in Computer Science. Which should I pick?
reply_content: Probably going to seem biased here, but I will pick UNSW. UNSW has one of the best computer science programs in Australia, with many of the students getting job offers from Google, Microsoft, Amazon, Apple, Dropbox and then relocating to the Bay Area. Just a note though, rankings of universities reflect reputation on research, and not in terms of undergraduate teaching quality. I’m not sure of the teaching quality and marking at SUNY Buffalo but I can confirm UNSW is very rigorous with regards to their computer science programs. I can confirm that some subjects mark not only to a bell curve but also harmonic and geometric means (which means you can get penalised harder for inconsistent performances). Not to mention that if you come from a country that is not either Australia or the United States, then you will most likely be paying full fee upfront. In that case, UNSW would be much cheaper. Not to mention that UNSW is easier to gain entry to (probably harder to exit because course is more difficult).

post_title: Is getting an EE & master of EE better than an EE & CS (both are the same amount of years at UNSW)?
post_content: Is getting an EE & master of EE better than an EE & CS (both are the same amount of years at UNSW)?
reply_content: Money aside. The question should be; What do you want to do? The money will come with both combo degrees. If you are already down with EE as a base, then math shouldn’t be a problem. CS is a lot of Math along with basic methodology and language particulars. That is, How many ways can you represent an If/Then statement or a FOR loop? On the ME route, IMHO, Strength of Materials and/or Fluid Mechanics is different and will broaden your knowledge of Engineering. A combo of EE and ME will most likely keep you busy in the electro-mechanical field while a combo of EE and CS may lead you in the direction of cloud and/or Data Science route. I can sympathize with you. I, personally, took the EE/CS route and am now a Data Scientist and am happy with the position.

post_title: What is the value of getting a graduate degree in information technology from UNSW Australia?
post_content: What is the value of getting a graduate degree in information technology from UNSW Australia?
reply_content: If you will be an international student and it’s a 2 year or longer course (two academic years (92 weeks) study) that is registered with CRICOS, there is value in doing such a course if you are looking to get PR in Australia in the future. You will meet the Australian Study Requirement (ASR) which means that: • you should be able to get a subclass 485 Temporary Graduate visa which will allow you to stay and work in Australia for up to 2 years • work in Australia on a 485 visa could provide points for Australian work experience • you will get additional points on the points test for meeting the ASR An Australian degree and work experience will help with getting a positive skills assessment from the Australian Computer Society (ACS) which is a mandatory requirement for any points tested visa

post_title: Should I take a master’s degree in Aviation Management at UNSW, Australia? I prefer a stable career path abroad and settlement opportunities.
post_content: Should I take a master’s degree in Aviation Management at UNSW, Australia? I prefer a stable career path abroad and settlement opportunities.
reply_content: Speaking as an immigrant to the United States, there is a chance to work in the US if there is a demand of people that far exceeds the supply of people in the Country you want to move to, you have a Company that want to hire you, and they are willing to sponsor you for a work visa. This is usually so difficult that you have to be highly specialized with work experience in that area for a company to go through the red tape to get this done. There is a second path you may want to investigate … that of military service. I beleive that there is a path to citizenship in the US if you serve as an enlisted soldier in the military. I did not do this personally, so you may want to check this out further.

post_title: Which university should I choose, one with a general high reputation but in a not so prosperous city or UNSW in Sydney for a double degree of advanced math and finance?
post_content: Which university should I choose, one with a general high reputation but in a not so prosperous city or UNSW in Sydney for a double degree of advanced math and finance?
reply_content: I don’t know specifically about the maths and finance offerings of UNSW or its competitors, so I will speak in general terms about universities and their reputations. UNSW has a generally high reputation, if that’s what matters to you. It is ranked 49th in the world in the QS rankings and 78th in the world in the Times Higher Education Rankings, and is a member of the Group of Eight, which tends to be considered the most prestigious group of universities in Australia. None I wonder which university you might be comparing UNSW with. In Australia, the universities that might tussle over who has the highest reputation are probably ANU, UQ, Monash and the Uni of Melbourne — all in prosperous, thriving cities. Good universities in cities with weaker economies include JCU and U. Tas., but neither would be likely to beat UNSW in overall reputation. Both Townsville and Hobart, despite weaker economies, are great lifestyle choices — I’m about to move to Townsville myself! Another possibility is that your second option is a global top 50 university in another country. Looking at the listings, this suggests an American ivy league university, since as far as I can see, the Australian, European and Asian universities that make the list are all in thriving cities. If the fees are not an issue and you have the opportunity to attend an ivy league university, I think you should take that opportunity.

post_title: Which university is better for Masters of commerce with a specialisation in finance: UNSW or Macquarie university, for a career in funds management for an international student? The costs of MQ is way cheaper
post_content: Which university is better for Masters of commerce with a specialisation in finance: UNSW or Macquarie university, for a career in funds management for an international student? The costs of MQ is way cheaper
reply_content: University of NSW or Macquaire University. Both are Metropolitan Unverisities — Campuses in tbe city of Sydney . I must sttess that all Australian Universities are State-funded (subsidised) universities, and their products are therefore Quality-assured. This means the educational products they offer must satisfy the quality level stipulated by the government under its AQF system. The University of NSW is a Sandstone University meaning, it is in the group of 8 Universities in Australia that are considered larger in terms of the size, length of establishment number of courses offered, large student population and boast to have greater reputation in tesearch. NSW uni can also boast about it's reputable management school known as tbe Australian Graduate School of Management. Macquaire Univetsity in the New group of university fast gaining reputation with its business school. Both Master of Comnerce degrees are recognised in Australia and overseas and as noted earlier quality-assured under AQF. The choice is clearly yours: Higher reputation of the course at a Sandstone — NSW university, greater fees versus cheaper fees at Macquaire University, but femembering both are recognised and quality-assured. Perhaps, NSW university is better known overseas. To decide, it is useful for you to get more course infomation from each of universites and check these with the Fund Management institutions in your country and gauge which one is better known and more recognised by those institutions. Hope this helps.

post_title: Looking at CSE course timetables at UNSW, I see most lectures durations are 3 hours. Why is it so? Is there a break in between? Do students find it possible to concentrate for the whole duration?
post_content: Looking at CSE course timetables at UNSW, I see most lectures durations are 3 hours. Why is it so? Is there a break in between? Do students find it possible to concentrate for the whole duration?
reply_content: I am a Master of Commerce student at UNSW. When it comes to the learning format, there are two types of lectures, which are 3 hours full lecture and 3 hours full seminar/tutorial. I got courses which were 3 hours full lecture and some courses on the 3 hours full seminar format. If you have a 3 hours full lecture, that usually means the total 3 hours is divided by 1.5 hours on lecture and 1.5 hours on tutorial. During the tutorial, the lecturer will assume you have read the assigned readings and case studies for that week. Therefore, you and your team would spend that 1.5 seminar hours working and thinking on how do the concepts apply to the practice through the case studies. Most of the time, the lecturer would ask if the students require some break in between lecture and seminar, and the answer to that question is usually ‘no. let’s jump to the seminar so we can finish early’. The 3 hours full seminar/tutorial (the second type), is normally for courses that require lots of in-class activities or talking. This type of learning is really effective if the course is all about doing or solving a real project. I got some courses which were taught in this format, and they were ‘Social Entrepreneurship Practicum’, ‘Negotiating class’, and some capstone courses. These courses generally require more student activities rather than learning new concepts (because the lecturer want you to learn new concepts using the readings they gave you, and apply it in class). In conclusion, there might be a break in between 3 hours lecture format, and wether your class is 3 hours lecture or 3 hours seminar, it really depends on what you study and the level of student activities in the class. Having said so, I personally think that it is really possible to concentrate during the whole duration. In fact, many students do not want to have a break in between the lecture and seminar. I hope it helps.
